    "body": "  A common scenario in serving is prefill with a cache hit — a new request shares a prefix with one already in flight. Instead of re-computing the prefix's KV state, we read it back from the cache and combine it with the genuinely new tokens.\r\n\r\n  The bug we kept patching\r\n\r\n  The attention kernel that does this work has a scratch buffer for compressing K and V into a fast format (FP8). That buffer is sized via a multiplier: N × max_tokens_per_call. The kernel then writes the actual K/V tokens into the buffer.\r\n\r\n  The bug: AD's MLA path was reading the full [past + new] KV in one shot and handing it all to the kernel in a single call. Under high concurrency, \"full\" became 84,252 tokens — but N = 1 only sized the buffer for 15,360. The kernel happily wrote 5.5× past the end of\r\n  its buffer → memory corruption → mysterious crashes downstream.\r\n\r\n  Two prior fixes:\r\n  - Bumped N from 1 → 16 (so 16 × 15,360 = 245,760 covers the observed worst case).\r\n  - Added a separate workspace tensor for captured CUDA graphs (orthogonal CUDA-graph stability problem).\r\n\r\n  The N=16 fix worked but was fragile: it was a hand-tuned constant chosen because it happened to be big enough for one workload. A bigger workload would re-introduce the bug.\r\n\r\n  The principled fix\r\n\r\n  Instead of making the buffer bigger to fit all the KV at once, call the kernel multiple times with smaller pieces of KV. Each call now writes ≤ N × max_tokens tokens, which the buffer is sized for. By construction, no overflow is possible.\r\n\r\n  Think of it like this: instead of trying to mail a 200-page document in one envelope (and buying bigger envelopes whenever someone writes a longer document), cut the document into chapters that always fit in a standard envelope, mail each chapter, and reassemble at the\r\n   destination.\r\n\r\n  How attention can be split across calls\r\n\r\n  Attention is essentially a weighted average. The naive split would be wrong — if I average half the values, then average the other half, then average those two averages, I lose the proper weighting.\r\n\r\n  The trick is that attention's softmax has two pieces of state: the running maximum logit (m) and the running sum of exponentials (s). If I compute attention on chunk A and chunk B separately, and I know (m_A, s_A) and (m_B, s_B), I can correctly combine the two partial\r\n   outputs into the full attention output. This is the same math behind FlashAttention's tiling.\r\n\r\n  The kernel was already capable of writing out these (m, s) stats per call. We just weren't using that feature. There's a separate \"merge\" kernel that takes (running output, partial output, running stats, partial stats) and combines them properly.\r\n\r\n  What the new code does\r\n\r\n  1. Plan upfront (host-side, runs before the GPU work): walk through which sequences have how much past KV, greedily pack their KV into iterations bounded by N × chunk_size tokens each. For each iteration, record:\r\n    - which sequences contribute (and how many tokens each)\r\n    - per-sequence read offset into the cache\r\n    - whether this sequence is making its \"first appearance\" (copy partial to running) or \"continuing\" (merge with running)\r\n  2. Execute the chunk loop: for each iteration:\r\n    - Read this chunk's slice of past KV from the cache.\r\n    - Run the attention kernel on it (with softmax-stats output enabled).\r\n    - Call the merge kernel to combine into the running result.\r\n  3. Final causal pass: the new tokens themselves — which haven't been mixed in yet — get one more attention pass with a causal mask, then merged in.\r\n\r\n  By the time we return, output holds the same answer the original one-shot call would have produced, but no individual kernel call ever wrote past its buffer.\r\n\r\n  Why N can shrink from 16 to 4\r\n\r\n  The packer in step 1 enforces the bound. If you give it more KV than N × chunk_size, it just creates more iterations. So N is no longer a \"hope this is enough\" upper bound — it's a knob trading per-call workspace against iteration count. 4 is the value the standard PyTorch backend uses, and the bench shows same perf as before and slightly better accuracy.\r\n\r\n  What didn't change\r\n\r\n  Three completely orthogonal things stayed put:\r\n  - The first kernel call (RoPE + cache write for the new tokens) is unchanged.\r\n  - The fresh-prefill path (no past KV) is unchanged — it has nothing to chunk.\r\n  - The decode path is unchanged — decode only processes 1 token per request.\r\n\r\n  Just the cache-reused prefill path got the loop treatment, mirroring how the standard PyTorch backend already does it.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<!-- This is an auto-generated comment: release notes by coderabbit.ai -->\r\n## Summary by CodeRabbit\r\n\r\n* **New Features**\r\n  * Added piecewise compilation configuration support for DeepSeek-R1 model.\r\n  * Added optional output buffer support for MLA attention operations.\r\n\r\n* **Improvements**\r\n  * Enhanced MLA attention with improved cache handling and chunked-prefill support.\r\n  * Improved buffer lifecycle management for CUDA-graph captured operations.\r\n<!-- end of auto-generated comment: release notes by coderabbit.ai -->\r\n\r\n<!--\r\nPlease write the PR title by following this template:\r\n\r\n**[JIRA ticket/NVBugs ID/GitHub issue/None][type] Summary**\r\n\r\nValid ticket formats:\r\n  - JIRA ticket: [TRTLLM-1234] or [FOOBAR-123] for other FOOBAR project\r\n  - NVBugs ID: [https://nvbugs/1234567]\r\n  - GitHub issue: [#1234]\r\n  - No ticket: [None]\r\n\r\nValid types (lowercase): [fix], [feat], [doc], [infra], [chore], etc.\r\n\r\nExamples:\r\n  - [TRTLLM-1234][feat] Add new feature\r\n  - [https://nvbugs/1234567][fix] Fix some bugs\r\n  - [#1234][doc] Update documentation\r\n  - [None][chore] Minor clean-up\r\n\r\nAlternative (faster) way using CodeRabbit AI:\r\n\r\n**[JIRA ticket/NVBugs ID/GitHub issue/None] @coderabbitai title**\r\n\r\nNOTE: \"@coderabbitai title\" will be replaced by the title generated by CodeRabbit AI, that includes the \"[type]\" and title.\r\nFor more info, see /.coderabbit.yaml.\r\n\r\n-->\r\n\r\n## Description\r\n\r\n<!--\r\nPlease explain the issue and the solution in short.\r\n-->\r\n\r\n## Test Coverage\r\n\r\n<!--\r\nPlease list clearly what are the relevant test(s) that can safeguard the changes in the PR. This helps us to ensure we have sufficient test coverage for the PR.\r\n-->\r\n\r\n## PR Checklist\r\n\r\nPlease review the following before submitting your PR:\r\n- PR description clearly explains what and why. If using CodeRabbit's summary, please make sure it makes sense.\r\n- PR Follows [TRT-LLM CODING GUIDELINES](https://github.com/NVIDIA/TensorRT-LLM/blob/main/CODING_GUIDELINES.md) to the best of your knowledge.\r\n- Test cases are provided for new code paths (see [test instructions](https://github.com/NVIDIA/TensorRT-LLM/tree/main/tests#1-how-does-the-ci-work))\r\n- Any new dependencies have been scanned for license and vulnerabilities\r\n- [CODEOWNERS](https://github.com/NVIDIA/TensorRT-LLM/blob/main/.github/CODEOWNERS) updated if ownership changes\r\n- Documentation updated as needed\r\n- Update [tava architecture diagram](https://github.com/NVIDIA/TensorRT-LLM/blob/main/.github/tava_architecture_diagram.md) if there is a significant design change in PR.\r\n- The reviewers assigned automatically/manually are appropriate for the PR.\r\n\r\n\r\n- [x] Please check this after reviewing the above items as appropriate for this PR.\r\n\r\n## GitHub Bot Help\r\n\r\nTo see a list of available CI bot commands, please comment `/bot help`.\r\n",
